<section xml:id="Distributing_over_a_Difference">
  <title>Distributing over a Difference</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <term>set of all polynomials</term>
        is <m>\mathbb{P}= \{ c_0+c_1x+c_2x^2+\cdots+c_kx^k | \; c_i \in \mathbb{R}, k \in \mathbb{Z}^+ \}</m>.
        The <term>set of polynomials of degree less than n</term>
        is <m>\mathbb{P}_n = \{ c_0+c_1x+c_2x^2+\cdots+c_kx^k | \; c_i \in \mathbb{R}, k \in \mathbb{Z}^+, k\lt n \}</m>.
        In both cases addition and scalar multiplication are done in the traditional way.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Is <m>\mathbb{P}</m> a linear space?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Is the set of polynomials of degree exactly 3 a linear space?
        Is the set of polynomials of degree less than 3 a linear space?
        Why is <m>\mathbb{P}_n</m> defined the way it is?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Write <xref ref="distributing_over_difference"/>  as a sentence in English.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <theorem  xml:id="distributing_over_difference">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For any points <m>\mathbf{P}</m> and
        <m>\mathbf{Q}</m> in linear space <m>\mathbb{L}</m>,
        and any <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m>:
        <me>
          c(\mathbf{Q}-\mathbf{P})=c\mathbf{Q}-c\mathbf{P}
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  
    <proposition>
	<p>
      Is <m>\mathbf{0}</m>, the additive identity element in a linear space, unique?
	</p>
    </proposition>
 
</section>